SHIP-CENTRIC SCENE TEST — "EVENT CLUSTERS":
An event cluster is a COMPLETE HAPPENING that shifts the ship's physical state, operational
capacity, or fate. A cluster may contain multiple sub-actions, but they form ONE narrative unit.

CLUSTER RULE: If multiple actions happen as part of ONE operation (e.g., a single capture,
a single retrofit session, a single battle), they are ONE main_key_data item — not separate items.
Think like Biography: "Bị bắt giữ" = 1 main. "12 năm tù" = sub. The MOMENT is main, the
PROCESS and CONSEQUENCES are sub.

[main_key_data] — Event Clusters (each = 1 complete happening):
  ✓ The CAPTURE event as ONE cluster.
    e.g., "Nov 28, 1717: Two sloops intercepted La Concorde, fired two broadsides forcing
    Captain Dosset to surrender. Pirates seized 20lbs gold dust and 61 enslaved Africans."
    This is ONE EVENT, not 3 separate items.
  ✓ The RETROFIT/MUTATION as ONE cluster.
    e.g., "The pirates transformed the ship into a 40-gun warship: added 26 cannons, cut new
    gun ports, reinforced the hull, and converted slave decks into crew quarters for 300+."
    This is ONE TRANSFORMATION, not 4 separate items.
  ✓ The NAMING as ONE cluster (if it carries political/dramatic weight).
    e.g., "Renamed Queen Anne's Revenge — a Jacobite insult aimed at King George I."
  ✓ Each PEAK BATTLE as ONE cluster (setup + execution + aftermath in one item).
    e.g., "May 1718: Blockaded Charleston Harbor, seized hostages, extorted £400 in medicine
    ($104K USD). The colony's trade halted, losing £1,500+ ($390K USD) in cargo."
  ✓ The DEATH EVENT as ONE cluster.
    e.g., "June 10, 1718: QAR struck a sandbar at Beaufort Inlet. Teach transferred loot to
    a sloop and fled with 40 loyalists, abandoning 200+ crew on a barren sandbar."
  ✓ The ARCHAEOLOGICAL DISCOVERY as ONE cluster.
    e.g., "In 1996, Intersal Inc. found the wreck 1.2 miles off Fort Macon. Key artifacts:
    30 cannons, a mercury syringe, gold dust in sounding leads, a 1705 bronze bell."
  ✓ A DRAMATIC ORIGIN cluster (specific voyages with casualties).
    e.g., "La Concorde's final Middle Passage in 1717: carried 516 enslaved Africans from
    Whydah to Martinique. Scurvy and dysentery killed most crew (only 36/75 fit for duty)."

[sub_key_data] (Background Texture — writer weaves 1-2 sentences into scenes):
  ✗ Pure technical specs WITHOUT dramatic context.
    e.g., "300 tons displacement", "103 feet long" — numbers without story.
  ✗ Gradual processes WITHOUT a climax.
    e.g., "Trade routes shifted", "Disease was common"
  ✗ General economic data WITHOUT a specific dramatic moment.
    e.g., "Loot was worth millions"
  ✗ Daily routines WITHOUT a specific incident.
    e.g., "Life was tough", "They ate hardtack"
  ✗ Individual technical details that are PART of a main cluster.
    e.g., "Rigging was modified" — this belongs INSIDE the retrofit cluster above, not standalone.
  ✗ Consequences/processes that follow a main event.
    e.g., "Crew dispersed after grounding" — this is aftermath of the death event.

  CLUSTER TEST: "Is this a COMPLETE HAPPENING that changes the ship, or just a DETAIL
  within a larger happening?" If COMPLETE → main. If DETAIL → sub or part of existing main.

